---
import "../styles/global.css";
import Header from "../components/Header.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
---

<!doctype html>

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />

    <meta
      name="viewport"
      content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"
    />

    <title>
      The Minimal Tolerance Theorem | Minimal Tolerance
    </title>

    <meta
      name="description"
      content="The formal statement, necessary conditions, burden of proof and corollary of the Minimal Tolerance Theorem by Federico Rodrigo."
    />

    <link
      rel="canonical"
      href="https://minimaltolerance.com/theorem"
    />
  </head>

  <body>
    <Header />

    <main>

      <!-- PAGE TITLE -->

      <section class="page-hero">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE FORMAL TEST
          </p>

          <h1>
            The Narrow Exception
          </h1>

        </div>

      </section>

      <!-- MAIN STATEMENT -->

      <section class="statement">

        <blockquote>
          The burden of proof rests entirely with those
          proposing coercion
        </blockquote>

      </section>

      <!-- INSTITUTIONAL LAST RESORT -->

  <section class="content-section content-section-alt">

  <div class="container">

    <p class="eyebrow">
      INSTITUTIONAL LAST RESORT
    </p>

    <h2>
      Neither moral nor efficient
    </h2>

    <p>
      The State is neither a moral nor an efficient solution.
      At most, it can be understood as an institutional
      technology of last resort, accepted only where voluntary
      coordination faces a demonstrated operational limit. Its
      use does not become legitimate merely because the
      alternatives appear insufficient
    </p>

    <p>
      Its possible tolerance is functional rather than ethical,
      exceptional rather than general, and restrictive rather
      than expansive. Even within that narrow role, the State
      remains costly, imprecise and vulnerable to abuse, which
      makes every extension beyond the proven necessity part of
      the problem the theorem is intended to contain
    </p>

  </div>

</section>

      <!-- FORMAL STATEMENT -->

      <section class="content-section">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            FORMAL STATEMENT
          </p>

          <h2>
            The theorem
          </h2>

          <blockquote class="formal-statement">
            In a non-ideal world, where the State is morally
            illegitimate and exhibits structural functional failures,
            its tolerance may be justified strictly on functional
            grounds only in cases where a structural free-rider
            problem renders stable voluntary provision unviable,
            under an exceptionally high evidentiary standard, and
            only when non-intervention would generate greater harm
            than the marginal harm introduced by state coercion
          </blockquote>

        </div>

      </section>

      <!-- THREE CONDITIONS -->

      <section class="theorem">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE THREE CONDITIONS
          </p>

          <h2>
            All three must hold simultaneously
          </h2>

          <p>
            A structural free-rider problem exists only when every
            condition below is satisfied
          </p>

          <div class="theorem-conditions">

            <article>

              <span>01</span>

              <h3>
                Effective non-excludability
              </h3>

              <p>
                It must be physically, technically or economically
                impossible to exclude non-payers from receiving the
                relevant benefit
              </p>

            </article>

            <article>

              <span>02</span>

              <h3>
                Relevant non-rivalry
              </h3>

              <p>
                One person’s use of the good must not meaningfully
                reduce the amount available to others
              </p>

            </article>

            <article>

              <span>03</span>

              <h3>
                Persistent voluntary collapse
              </h3>

              <p>
                Voluntary provision must remain persistently unviable
                for reasons not caused by removable regulatory or
                legal obstacles
              </p>

            </article>

          </div>

        </div>

      </section>

      <!-- BURDEN OF PROOF -->

  <section class="content-section content-section-alt">

  <div class="container">

    <p class="eyebrow">
      THE BURDEN OF PROOF
    </p>

    <h2>
      No presumption. No analogical expansion
    </h2>

    <p>
      Importance, collective benefit or dissatisfaction with a
      voluntary outcome does not establish a functional
      justification for coercion. Identifying a difficulty cannot
      validate the proposed remedy without evidence that the
      intervention will improve the situation rather than
      reproduce its limitations in another form
    </p>

    <p>
      The exception must be demonstrated independently in each
      case and cannot be presumed, generalized or extended by
      analogy. Failure to satisfy any one of the required
      conditions leaves the presumption against intervention
      intact
    </p>

  </div>

</section>

      <!-- COROLLARY -->

     <section class="content-section">

  <div class="container">

    <p class="eyebrow">
      COROLLARY
    </p>

    <h2>
      The default remains non-intervention
    </h2>

    <blockquote class="formal-statement">
      Where no structural free-rider problem exists—or where
      viable voluntary mechanisms are available—state
      intervention lacks functional justification and must be
      presumed illegitimate by default
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      The corollary preserves voluntary provision as the general
      rule and prevents an exceptional justification from becoming
      a permanent license for intervention. Where individuals can
      still coordinate through viable voluntary arrangements, no
      institutional necessity has been demonstrated
    </p>

    <p class="plain-language">
      Where there is no structural free-rider problem,
      there is no State
    </p>

  </div>

</section>

      <!-- APPLICATIONS -->

      <section class="content-section content-section-alt">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            APPLICATIONS
          </p>

          <h2>
            Testing the boundary
          </h2>

          <p>
            The theorem matters only if it can distinguish genuine
            institutional necessity from political convenience,
            paternalism and dissatisfaction with voluntary outcomes
          </p>

          <div class="buttons">

            <a href="/applications" class="primary">
              Explore the Applications
            </a>

          </div>

        </div>

      </section>

    </main>

    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
